  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Health and multi-sectorial Assistance to vulnerable people affected by displacement in Nangarhar province</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed action comes in response to the needs in health, wash and non-food items for people affected by displacement (returnees, both documented and undocumented and conflict-induced IDPs) in Nangarhar province. The sudden wave of return movements from Pakistan, added to the existing caseload of people displaced by conflict, is putting access to health services and potable water at risk for thousands of vulnerable households living in makeshift camps. Data collected from PU-AMI during its routine emergency intervention, consolidated with specific secondary data collected during recent weeks, show an increase of beneficiaries of health services, putting the capacity of the system to deliver at strain.

PU-AMI, already active in Emergency Response in Nangarhar province, will provide access to basic healthcare for 66&#x2019;000 individuals, both returnees (documented and undocumented) and conflict-induced IDPs, unable to access timely assistance in overloaded or inaccessible health facilities through dedicated Mobile Health Systems, scaling-up an intervention already ongoing since earlier this year through PU-AMI ECHO funded project.
Additionally, in order to prevent water-related diseases, PU-AMI will provide assistance vulnerable households with NFI and hygiene kits to enable access to drinking water and proper hygiene conditions. Indeed, PU-AMI Households &#x2018;visits in makeshifts camps reports a large prevalence of water-related diseases like diarrhea, one of the most treated symptoms by PU-AMI teams on the field, particularly for children. In this regard, PU-AMI is planning to assist 3,000 vulnerable households with hygiene kits to allow provision of safe drinking water and ensure proper hygiene conditions, in order to reduce prevalence of water-related diseases. 

Finally, at the onset of harsh winter, PU-AMI will also assist 2,000 households particularly vulnerable through the distribution of NFI / Winterization kits in order to limit the impact of cold temperature and fragile living conditions on the health profile of the affected population.</narrative>
  </description>
